{"text": "The narrative takes a while to arrest the player because it exposes their characters and ties them to the plot very slowly and gradually. During the early minutes, we're just spectators. As in The Gray Garden and Wadanohara, here we also have a lot of dialogues for the presentation of the story and involvement with the plot, but the main difference is the option to skip some cutscenes with the shift. The gameplay is the same as you're used to: exploring the scenario and solving puzzles - very complicated, by the way. The mapping is a bit confusing for all floors, corridors and castle doors interlocking in a somewhat illogical way, making it almost impossible for the player to create a \"mind map\" of where they are and where they should go, go round and round to get into rooms that seem to have been put away from all the shortcuts to test the player's patience. Soundproofing is effective by having ambient sounds to keep the atmosphere of suspense and songs tightly tucked in at energetic moments in order to cause more pressure and anxiety in who is playing. The graphics are normal, they are even \"charming\", but the big surprise is in the art created to illustrate certain moments during the gameplay, superior if compared to previous ones of the author.", "appid": "749840", "steamid": "profiles/76561198145502917", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1549022400.0}
