{"text": "Fae Tactics is a Tactical-RPG, like Final Fantasy Tactics, the yardstick of the genre. As a reminder, the basics of the gameplay are to move these units on a map covered with squares (movement imitated to a certain number of squares), attack the enemies and then position yourself to one side for the next turn. Indeed, it is important to position yourself well because an attack from the side or from the back will do more damage, and it is also valid on the opponents. Where Fae Tactics stands out is offering a summoning system at the start of each turn. These are actually additional members of your team made up of monsters that you have defeated and whose card you have acquired. You can set up your allies in advance or do it before the start of the fight if necessary. This is different from unit management in other titles, but it is true that it amounts to about the same in the end. But that's not all. There is also a magic system, where you can set up three different powerful spells, and which you can cast with any of your units before its movement phase and when magic is available (i.e. when the cooldown is finished). This is interesting because it adds a new possibility to a character's turn. Here too, you can set the spells in advance or before the start of the fight. A final point of gameplay that is innovative is the passive skills of units, both allied and enemy. Each character has a passive skill that activates when the character does not take an action (you can still move him before). When you validate the end of your turn, your skill is triggered. This can be a zone of protection within which each unit located there and being attacked will not suffer damage because it is the defendant who will take, a self-regeneration of MP or shield points, an increase in combined attack chance, etc. Suddenly, this increases the strategic dimension, because it will sometimes be necessary rather to delay a turn to have the passive skill bonus before making an attack which will be more devastating. In addition to this, each time you level up, you will earn a point to place on a line of your choice: offense, defense and special. This allows us to customize our heroes a bit, in addition to the weapon and a scroll. Fae Tactics is a pixel art style 3D isometric game. Don't expect fine graphics that can't be seen a pixel! However, the game is very beautiful, very colorful, and the animations are neat. In any case, no problem to make it run, whatever the machine! The soundtrack is also very nice, reminiscent of music from the 16-bit era. They are very pretty and set the mood well, catchy during fights, with a western air, and more relaxing during dialogue phases. Fae Tactics really convinced me. We are certainly in a tactical like we can see many others, but the title brings some welcome subtleties. The pixel-art style is very nice and the soundtrack looks like a western too.", "appid": "995980", "steamid": "profiles/76561198077624633", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1601726400.0}
