{"text": "Initially I couldn't even start the game, I tried many of the fixes that had been posted and had no luck, finally I found one that works and so I sat down to play. After finally getting the game to work, seriously paradox this launch was shoddy as hell, I can give you my first impressions. (For reference I played at a tribe in \"Britain\") ---------------------------------------- Events: Events that happen seem pretty lacklustre, from what I've seen it feels like there's only around 5 - 10 and all that changes is the character names, they certainly don't seem to really have any real effect on the game or your characters, a bit of loyalty change here or there etc and not much else. ---------------------------------------- Economy: The economy needs some balancing, getting enough Oratory power to do anything takes forever as too many things require it, whereas from my experience you'll be sitting on a pile of Religious & Military power that only functions to exist when your omen ticks off for religious power (or a random stability drop happens) or as a side tech tree in terms of the military power, which I've seen possibly be relevant in one event so far which required like 25 out of the 1000 I had. The trading system with its surpluses etc is an interesting idea, but if you play the game as presumably intended and take over others peoples lands your access to anything to import will be screwed. ---------------------------------------- Research: The research system is more of a Stellaris one in this game (or MOO2 if you like), which is fine, the trouble being that if you do invest in research like I did (currently about 100 years ahead with no trouble at all) all the tech (small incremental buffs to things) is just going to fly by as you most likely won't be getting enough Culture points to purchase it all and each new tech level hides the previous options you unlocked only to be revealed when you clear one of the newer ones away.  I also can't help but feel like you should maybe be able to purchase Military tech with military power visa versa. Research has a big impact on the game, but you won't feel like it does as you're not really unlocking anything new, just buffing already existing things. ---------------------------------------- Characters: The characters in the game don't have much of a personality, sometimes their little perks do effect events, the ultra common event where a petitioner appears at court worrying that someone was going to kill her mysteriously and you can either comfort her or take the money she wants to leave you in her will got a third event because my character had the Lunacy perk, a third option that said \"Kill her in a Mysterious way\" which was funny, but so far the only example I've seen of this kind of thing. Aside from that, there's no real way to interact with your characters, 90% of the options will be greyed out for some stupid reason, why can't I imprison etc people when I want for a bit of tyranny? (Presumably because it would break the rebellion mechanics) and they merely sit there as stat boxes, you can't influence their actions like in CK2 and your children also can't be guided into a role you might want filling from an heir, infact I often forgot I even had children because nothing bad even happens when someone not of my family inherits the throne/chiefdom etc anyway apart from one person being a bit pissy for a bit. Christ even Stellaris leaders had more personality than this. ---------------------------------------- Summary: I'm still enjoying the game so far but I don't know why, as I can see its flaws and it's no where near as good as it should be, you get the honest feeling that the filler that made other Paradox games like CK2 great (A wide array of events that interact with the world) has been cut for DLC down the road, because I Refuse to believe Paradox hasn't learnt their lesson on what works by now and that the meme(?) of Paradox games being empty on content at launch seems to be entirely true. The game is broken, bland and barren. Wait till they add more content and fix all the game breaking bugs and for the love of god when the game is fixed don't reward them for this behaviour and don't buy more content until the vanilla base game has been fleshed out till it feels like a full game. They need to learn they can't just treat their customers like an ATM in the same way Bethesda does with their games being unfinished content wise.", "appid": "859580", "steamid": "profiles/76561198009560429", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1556193600.0}
