{"text": "Now I've been a gamer for a long time. I know this is a sentiment that people throw around loosely to sound like their opinions matter more than others on the subject of gaming. But no. For real, I have been gaming for a loooong time. Nearly 40 years long. I'm not going to say I'm the oldest gamer ever. But I've been gaming long enough that I can say I actually grew up in the era where the Atari 2600 was a dominant machine. I can remember playing the cheap plastic controller that had the rubber coating around the joystick part. I actually broke a few of those on games like Activision's Decathalon. Oh, how my parents hated that. One of my least favorite controllers in retrospect by the way. But we had those. We also had the paddles, with the rotating knob. Such simpler times. Years gone by, and I have graduated gradually to higher end games. More complexity. Better graphics. Better stories. Better, everything. But I still have a fond memory of the old Atari days. So when Atari released a compilation, I was quick to snatch it up. But then I was quickly reminded... Hey man... Atari sucks!  No, not the consoles they made. The Atari 2600 and its predecessors (Jaguar excluded) had some decent games. But the thing is, very few of them were actually developed by Atari. No. The fond memories I had of this system were actually from other developers. Other devs were making good use of the hardware and gave us such classics as H.E.R.O., Pitfall 1 and 2, Frogger, Dig Dug, Space Invaders, and a lot more. Now Atari on the other hand made a bunch of games themselves, but sadly this is a case of quantity over quality. Only a few of their games could even be considered classics. Luckily, those classics are here, buried in a pile of crap.  For those willing to sift through the garbage, you'll find such classics as Yars Revenge, Crystal Castles, and a handful of others. But you'll also find a lot of crap. And I do mean a LOT of crap in the 2600 games. Luckily there are a select few Arcade variants in here as well. Not a lot of good ones, but you can experience the better versions of classics such as Crystal Castles, Centipede, Milliepede, Asteroids and a few others. Even the arcade version of Pong. Yeah, Pong. The game every kid wants! Hell, I did not even want Pong back then.  All in all, for those that can brave this collection of games, the controls are fine (controller recommended though). The presentation is very serviceable. It's not a terrible collection as far as packaging goes. But don't expect to spend a lot of time past the initial nostalgia freakout on these games. There are far better compilations available of classic games available. And for those that want a good Atari 2600 fix, might I suggest hunting down a copy of Activision Anthology (Not on Steam sadly).  Bottom line: If you grew up with an Atari 2600 and actually recognize some of these games as having played them yourself, it might be worth a look. for everyone else, unless you are a collector, I'd probably avoid this one.", "appid": "400020", "steamid": "profiles/76561197979043237", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "40", "votes_funny": "6", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1595678400.0}
