{"text": "I don't usually write reviews for games, as I am by no means a professional at this and I tend to obsess over one game at a time (and not every game can truly hook me) and often times am not able to put much time into a game before jumping to another. I do believe we should give any game a fair shake, and truly let them speak for themselves, but the process can take a good amount of time, especially when you have a review in mind. I lean towards reviewing games that are truly exceptional, for good or for bad. This might or might not be one of those, depending on how you look at it. I did not originally intend on writing a review for Mercenary Kings, but the very little time I've put into it, I couldn't have any fun whatsoever. It is absolutely astounding how a game can be so well made, look so good, and still fail completely to interest in any capacity, but Mercenary Kings manages to do just that: most of the problems stem from the fact that the gameplay present in it is just not... fun. At all. The game is not *broken*, by any stretch of the imagination, and I've certainly played worse games, I'd even go as far as saying some of those terrible, broken games were more fun because of the added character: Take Deadly Premonition, for example, a terrible game to play, but with so much character and life that makes it one of the most enjoyable experiences in gaming. I can't say Mercenary Kings has no character to it, but it still lacks a lot. So what went wrong? For one, the controls. Oh, the controls. The default controls have you using WASD to walk, and IJKL to do actions such as jumping (which requires you holding the button to jump higher), rolling, shooting and dodging, although you can also dodge by double tapping a direction. I couldn't get used to the controls at all, and believe me, I tried. At one point I got fed up with them and just decided to change the controls... only to realize that you can't change the controls while in-game. You have to go to the main menu, leaving the game without knowing when was the last time the game saved, because there is no save-on-demand function. Because they have an autosave function, where they tell you not to \"turn off\" your computer whilst saving. I then spent what felt like an ungodly amount of time trying to get the commands right, but they won't let you assign an action to more than one key, so if used to another game's controls and you're just trying to get a feel for it, you can't try multiple keybindings at a time to help you ease in. I've tried many many different combinations, but nothing ever felt right, and everytime I failed to find something I was comfortable with, I'd have to go back to the main menu, rebind everything, get really confused because I rebound the \"advance\" or \"back\" menu buttons, then get back in the game to try it all again. After some time, I just rolled with a setup I wasn't comfortable with, thinking \"hey, if I can't get used to it I might get my controller and come back to it\", even though I deeply disliked the reloading mechanic, where you have to time your reloads, and failing the mini-game results in longer reload times, but the game will automatically start a reload when you run out of bullets and keep firing, whereas pressing the shoot button again will *not* reload the gun, you have to press the designated reload button (Space for default, and although I personally think no action should ever use Space outside of Jumping, there was no better button for it), or wait the arbitraty time the bar takes to fill up on itself. I should clarify, I'm a PC gamer, and I use my keyboard for every single game I can, and unless the game is actually unplayable, I will go through the trouble of getting my controller to play the game, such as in the case of Dust: An Elysian Tail and Guacamelee, both of which are great games, and I did not mind playing them on controller at all. I then tried my first mission: The game will let you pick which missions in your tier you want to do in which order, and then you get onto the main mission, which lets you advance to the next tier of missions; simple stuff. Decided to do the collection mission, where you have to get three pelts as well as having an extra objective to collect a feather. I proceeded to kill some animals for the pelts before realizing that there was a time limit for the mission, and that exploring all around was actually detrimental to the objective -- what the game actually wanted me to do was grind out the same enemy over and over to get the required pelts, because once the screen scrolls a little bit, every enemy you've killed in that area will respawn again, and you can just run back to them and not have to worry about where every other enemy spawns. I should mention that I'm one of the few people in the world who actually does not mind grinding at all, and in fact can even find it fun depending on the game, but grinding for feathers and pelts felt awkward and out of place. Your loot isn't guaranteed, most enemies will drop varying levels of stuff, which you collect to then upgrade stuff in your base, although the game expects you to know what drops what, and I know if there was another mission later on which required the collecting of 50 Ron Paul 2012 bumper stickers I'd probably have to waste most of the alotted 15 or so minutes killing 20 rats to see if they drop the damn buggers. And that's nowhere near the thing that made me most frustrated. I completed the first mission in something like five minutes, five minutes. To get a feather and three pelts from enemies I *knew* how to grind. I then jumped into the second mission, an elimination mission -- the premise simple: Kill 8 snipers. Thought it'd be easy as pie -- until I actually started playing and realizing the tutorial had not prepared me anywhere near enough: The snipers do not respawn, but everything else does. The area of the mission is huge, and there's EXACTLY 8 snipers, of which you must find and kill all. You WILL get lost, and WILL have to backtrack all the way through to MAYBE, just MAYBE find the place where the last sniper is... I didn't. I kept getting hit by the same annoying enemies I refused to kill over and over again just to avoid the reloading mechanic, and eventually perished after my three or so lives ended before I could rerun the area I had already rerun twice a third time. The worst part is, I'm pretty sure one of the snipers I killed was in the same exact place of another sniper I had previously killed, but no other location had a sniper that respawned, which made me really confused. By that point, any interest I had in the game had been absolutely crushed, my time spent (most of which was at the menus) wasted, and my patience wore thin. I'm sure if I had spent more time with the game I would surely have gotten better at it and maybe even had fun, but the thing is: I do not want to. Nothing in this game, outside the beautiful Metal Slug-esque graphics make me want to keep playing it, and I really feel I should be wanting to play this game because it looks so competent, but does not play like so. I think it'd be unfair to talk about the soundtrack, as I've only heard a handful of songs at most, but I should mention that the few I've heard were fairly bland, and that really got enhanced by the fact that the music just would not loop properly upon staying in the menus for too long (which as mentioned before, I did plenty of). I'm not recommending this game on the account of not having a good time with it, but the fact is, if you do not mind grinding, can get used to any control scheme (think Dark Souls, for example), and like the idea of rerunning the same mission to get better at it and get record times, you might even like this game. If it's on sale, you might want to give it a shot, even if it's just to play as Jill Sandwich for a few moments before moving onto a better game.", "appid": "218820", "steamid": "profiles/76561197994316647", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1437652800.0}
