{"text": "I know what you're thinking, most likely. I know this is one of, if not, the most successful indie franchise of all time, and you're probably saying  . But I got solid reasons to hate it. First of all, I want to clear up that FNAF 1 isn't a bad game. I must recognice it was a pretty good game, and pretty original too. But, my reason to hate FNaF, doesn't come from the game. But rather the whole series. Why? Because in less than one year, Scott Cawthon released (at least)  , without actually improving the gameplay, and overexploiting it. What do I mean? That this is just a mold of every single FNaF game ever released. Yeah, FNaF 2 had no doors. FNaF 3 had traps for the only actual enemy, but, do you see a gameplay alteration? Do you see an actual improvement between FNaF 1 and 4? No, you don't. You see Scott basically altering the MECHANICS of the game, but NOT improving the game. He said FNaF 3 would be the last game of the   franchise. But, a month after that, we see FNaF 4 up on the steam store! Why? Because his fanbase is not only mostly consisted of kids that aren't used to the point 'n click genre, but because he knows that if he just adds the word \"Freddy\" on one of his games, the sales of it will rise up, mostly because people will think they're going to play something new. And it could easily be a simulator of Freddy taking a dump over a computer. But, where's the FNaF on it? On the Freddy sprite.  As nonsensical as it sounds, it's right. FNaF 3 is basically a game that could EASILY be deleted of the franchise, and yet NO timeline-related issues would occur! Because the lore itself isn't even present in the game. Whenever you're buying FNaF 2, 3 or 4, you're just buying this game I'm reviewing right now, only that it has altered game mechanics.  you may say. Yes. It does have minigames. But does it alter the story of 5 murderous robots that are trying to kill you? Nope. It's an add in. A filler. A way to fill the game, so it feels new. Scott is just taking the same game over and over again, editing it a little bit, altering the way the characters look and behave, and replacing the game system over and over again. First it's a tablet and 2 doors. Then it's a light, a mask, and a tablet. Then a reset system button, with the ghosts of the past characters. And now? Yet another new concept. Don't get yourself fooled. If you're playing the game for the story, it would be better to watch a gameplay rather than spending your money on a carbon copy of a past game. Simple as that. Scott is taking your money, and he's releasing games faster and faster, because each time he says \"Five nights at freddy's\", lots of little kids that haven't ever played a point 'n click get their wallets ready to buy the exact same game again, only that with a different mechanic. Just like Toy Story 2 and 3. Both blockbuster movies. Both go the same way. Both end the same way. And it still made TONS of cash. Same with FNaF.", "appid": "319510", "steamid": "profiles/76561198039292424", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "9", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1438344000.0}
