{"text": "GreedFall - a game so confused about what it wants to be that it ends up being anywhere from barely functional to outright broken in the majority of present mechanics.   While on paper the combat system might seem like it would work and function properly there is nothing further from the truth. There is no stamina bar or cooldown on your blocking ability so you are able to just spam a single button and win every combat encounter as a \"perfectly\" timed block will allow you to get a free hit in without the need to push any other button. This technique doesn't work against ranged or boss enemies that can go through your block, but fear not, there is also a \"dodge\" option, that will allow you to dodge infinitely, evading every attack, while your companions attack the boss. It is possible that the boss will aggro them, but more often than not they will just glitch out and never attack your companions. I was able to recreate this a couple of times and defeat bosses using only my dodge ability on the >>>HARD<<< (second hardest) difficulty. On top of that you also have the option of using firearms that shoot fast enough as to allow you to stun-lock anyone that can be staggered (ammo needed to use these firearms is also dirt cheap, and accessible at every merchant, you also get an option of crafting ammo on top of that, just in the off chance you run out of ammo). Abusing the combat system like this is generally not needed when you face human enemies, they are incredibly easy and have no chance of even hitting you in melee combat as they have slow, well-telegraphed attacks that deal less damage than you'd expect. Monster enemies on the other hand generally share a set of attacks that aims to stun-lock you into a coma before you can dodge a single attack, or poison you with ranged attacks, it becomes even more evident as you encounter new animals that all share the same skillset, despite having different visuals.   I have not encountered a combat system so broken to its core since ELEX.     Once again, in theory, the system present in this game seems to be fairly reasonable, while it does manage to be functional it has some aspects that seem rather bizarre, such as the charisma system that you can put up to 3 points into, that increases your chances of passing the RNG speech check by 25% each point to a total of a 75% increase, sadly there is no reason to put any points into it as a cape (clothing item) will always give you 1 charisma, and the game has no system to prevent you from reloading until you successfully  pass a skill check.     While certain quests did seem interesting at first, majority of that interest was sadly lost due to poor writing, lack of logical connection between quest updates and what you actually hear in a conversation, lack of any choice for the player, or even ability to acknowledge that the \"super-secret training camp\" that an NPC has to take 6 in-game hours to look for is the same camp we encountered while on a leisurely stroll just minutes ago (with that same NPC). On top of that many characters are written in such a way that I have begun to question whether they're meant to be mentally handicapped or if it's just the dev's inability to write believable characters, most of which feel incredibly stereotypical and predictable. My favorite quest is possibly one where you have to get inside a morgue to inspect a body of a \"young lad\", sadly the devs did not seem to have a model of a young, dead soldier, so they just replaced the \"young lad\" with a heavily wrinkled old man, undoubtedly in his prime, sadly not intentional.   Quests are also very obviously contrived, stereotypical, boring and copy-pasted fetch quests, with the occasional slightly more interesting one thrown into the mix. Same applies to the enemies that are just dropped in groups of 3-5 into a region to slow you down a bit. Possibly my favorite group of enemies is one located in New Serene (the second city that you encounter) where 3 lowly bandits \"ambush\" you every single time you pass the guardhouse, which is filled with guards, that are meant to prevent crime from happening.     While graphically the game is certainly not ugly the same sadly cannot be said about characters and their animations, but there has been plenty said about that in other reviews, what I haven't seen mentioned however is the fact that the MENSA member responsible for proofreading all the text in this game cannot tell the difference between \"there\" and \"their\". That same person also cannot decide how to spell other words such as \"phantom\" (fantom), evidently a proof that the game would benefit from more playtesting and development time.     \"Engage in a core roleplaying experience – achieve quests and complete objectives in a multitude of different ways – through combat, diplomacy, deception, or stealth.\"     There is no diplomacy, there is no deception, stealth is always forced on you, the penalty for not stealthing is a bunch of XP and free loot. You don't have a choice who joins your party, you don't have a choice how to punish people that cross you, you don't have a choice how to approach combat in missions, and in most cases, you don't even have a choice who to side with. You do get a choice whether you want to spare or kill a nameless soldier that is never mentioned again tho, so that's pretty big.   This is a fully linear game, there is no exploration, there are no interesting locations, there are no interesting choices, no alternatives routes (other than a skill check that skips an enemy or two). All of that is topped off with an absolute lack of finish and attention to detail.   Do NOT believe all the reviews calling this game the next RPG godsend the like of which you haven't experienced since the original Dragon Age, comparable to The Witcher, this is nothing more than an unfinished, confused action game with awful combat and questionable dialogue.", "appid": "606880", "steamid": "profiles/76561198008454025", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "112", "votes_funny": "15", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1568462400.0}
