{"text": "Our story opens on a mysterious train ride to somewhere. The protagonist reads a letter from his lover begging for help and a rescue. Through the train’s window, you’re greeted by beautiful vistas of the Welsh countryside circa the 1890s. Before long you arrive at the village of Sker’s train station. As you exit the mostly mundane train, you begin to feel dread slithering up inside of you. Suddenly, there’s nothing mundane about where you’re standing now. The world is still beautiful, but something is off.  As you make your way toward Sker Hotel (the train disappearing behind a bend in the woods) you gaze upon signs of faded glory, ghosts of what this place once was, now choked to death by overgrown vegetation and the ever-present indifference of nature. Up the dirt path you go, pushing past the decrepit gate of Sker Hotel, toward your endangered lover.  You feel it now. Somewhere, hiding beneath this faded, horror-masking glamour, there’s something that wants to kill you.    The tragedy of Maid of Sker has little to do with its town, hotel, or even its titular maid. No, the real tragedy is that you’ve already experienced the best the game has to offer. Glorious exposition, coupled with incredibly deft sound design and beautifully realized visuals, eventually gives way to a tedious game of hide and seek that lacks all the fun of the children’s game. The threat of something coming, and the anticipation of what that might be, it turns out, is infinitely more anxiety-inducing than anything you’re going to be dealing with at the hotel.  Our monsters are the hotel’s “guests,” transformed by something plot (and spoiler) related. They’re all more or less blind (more) and mindless horrors (less), stalking the halls searching for a victim. In order to navigate the hotel, you must circumvent its inhabitants. If they hear you, they will chase you. And the game’s systems talk to each other well in that regard. If you move, you’ll make noise, if you make noise, they will hear, and if they hear, you’ll want to run—which makes noise. And that’s the lion’s share of the entire experience.  The problem is, there’s absolutely no reason to hurry.  So, actually, the question becomes whether or not you’re willing to be bored enough to play the game effectively. Are you willing to sit and wait for something that resembles a blind 90 year old man (they’re all men; I guess the women took one look at the gate and went to the Holiday Inn) to lurk by so you can quietly, and simply, move past undetected? And trust me, you will do that. Over and over. It’s Pac-Man except no one gets eaten. That would be too scary or something. Instead these evil granddad creatures just want to, well, punch you. That’s really it. If they find you, they just want to smack you around a little. Which only seems like a mildly inconvenient punishment for whatever has them so upset.   So if the enemy isn’t intimidating, and the results of being captured aren’t frightening, how is Maid of Sker actually supposed to scare you?  The game suffers an identity crisis trying to manufacture something that might actually horrify the player. Occasionally spikes will shoot through a bed, or a mutilated corpse may lie incinerated in a bathtub, or a trap door may send you down a deep, dark tunnel. And even, God forbid, a Jack-in-the-Box might spring! But none of it amounts to anything particularly scary because most of it lacks compelling context. It just exists. Obviously these elements taken by themselves have the characteristics of something scary. No one is denying that. Which is what makes the entire endeavor of Maid of Sker so damn odd. The creators have a good handle on horror aesthetics, as those aesthetics are all over the game, but they just don’t know how to manage them. In pictures, Maid of Sker is indeed horrifying because it’s loaded with beautiful, malevolent imagery that works wonders. The issue is that there’s nothing adequately frightening holding this malevolence together. It’s just a haunted house. Not a real one; the pop-up ones that you venture through on Halloween. The ones that employ scary things like vampires, mummies, and fat men with fake chainsaws. But why would a vampire, a mummy, and a corpulent chainsaw wielder be hanging out together? No one ever asks that, do they?  Maid of Sker should have.  The game needs a narrative that joins all of its scary imagery into a context that means something important. And, in the early parts, it does a decent job of delivering that. But the narrative undoes itself.  The main culprit for this is in the way the game delivers its dialogue. Maid of Sker allows the player to choose which lines of dialogue to say, but oddly never gives the main character, Thomas, the agency of asking anything sensical. Besides, they’re not really options anyway. They only provide an illusion of choice, playing at being dynamic based on your selections. It’s downright infuriating that there are no choices to actually ask something, I don’t know, logical? Questions like, “Why, if you love me, did you invite me to a place where I am most likely going to die?” Thomas, to the contrary, treats everything happening like it’s an entirely normal inconvenience. As if, at some point in all our lives, we’re going to walk into a haunted hotel. As you do. You just gotta accept it and deal with it. He’s a bit of a buffoon. A video game caring about its plot, while admirable, doesn’t mean that its plot is good by default. In fact, it may actually make the game worse by unnecessarily drawing attention to its weaknesses. I never questioned the silly puzzles in the original Resident Evil, but then again, it never asked me to. Thomas is also a goofy guy mechanically! In order to not make noise, Thomas can place his hand over his mouth to avoid breathing (why does he breathe so loud?) so you can sneak past enemies. If Thomas stands too close to a fire (by close I mean several feet away), he coughs, which makes noise and alerts your foes. If there’s too much dust in the air, same thing. I didn’t learn much about Thomas, but I did learn that the man will cough if he doesn’t cover his mouth.  And running? Forget about it. A short dash has Thomas sucking air like he just ran a marathon.    It’s the creator’s  job to make mechanics that add strategy and tension, but Maid of Sker does it at a high cost to the game’s verisimilitude. Is this guy asthmatic? Does he have TB or something? That could actually have been an interesting device in a game where breathing makes you vulnerable. As is, it’s entirely too (in)convenient that the very thing that Thomas needs to be—quiet—is the very thing he sucks at. This chronic hypoxia must explain why he can’t jump. Too much air required. Because if Thomas could simply jump (or step) over a couple of three-foot-high boxes, he’d have saved the day in half the time. But instead of jumping, Thomas would rather take unnecessary detours past things that want to kill him (and punch him!).  Thomas is either incompetent or the least athletic person in Wales. Or both. The game isn't a total waste. It is, as mentioned, stunning to look at. Even if I’m not entertained by its content, the game’s visual and audio fidelity command attention. But it just isn’t scary. Which is a problem because it's a horror game.  And based on that, perhaps solely, I can’t recommend it. (This game was received for free)", "appid": "826940", "steamid": "profiles/76561198081614663", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "86", "votes_funny": "11", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1596801600.0}
