{"text": "Toby is a humanoid being with horns whose friends have been kidnapped by demonic-looking red-eyed villains. Your side quest is to reach and release them, with a lot of them found in hidden alcoves and just out of sight of the beaten path. But the main mission is to negotiate the game’s puzzle-platforming sequences, continuously avoiding Toby’s death. This game is obviously heavily 'inspired' by Limbo but it maintains its own personality, being a shorter and coloured proposal. Although the game looks pretty nice with its art style making use of shadow and minimalistic design for its 2D protagonist. It can't escape having a cartoony feel that doesn't suit the dark tone it's aiming for.  Controls are fairly simple, with a jump button allowing you to make leaps between platforms and an action button for pulling levers. In the opening few levels, the platforming is kept relatively simple and straightforward, but as you progress deeper into the game you're faced with more complex and twitch based sections. These sections don't mesh well with the floaty jumping and leave you with plenty of frustrating deaths. Seriously, lots of them. The puzzle solving, on the other hand, is mostly a much more enjoyable experience. The difficulty is scaled almost perfectly here. You'll encounter physics based puzzles and simple switch puzzles, as well as more complex puzzles involving the use of light and a need to pay close attention to your surrounding environment. Unfortunately, there are a few conundrums present that are mostly just left up to guess work. These puzzles can thankfully be brute forced rather quickly, but it still impedes your enjoyment. In conclusion, Toby The Secret mine is a decently yet frustrating 2d platformer for someone looking play another puzzle platformer that won't take up much time. Buy you probably, prefer to give Limbo a try instead. Thanks   for this gift! <3", "appid": "395160", "steamid": "profiles/76561198983211883", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1600689600.0}
