{"text": "You can't expect much from a game this cheap, and even the game even tells you this; nonetheless, I can't recommend this game. I find the concept is interesting, I could laugh at the lame jokes but I can't enjoy the rigidity of the animations, the physics that more often than not hinder your movements and make you feel covered in glue or another sticky substance. This is a randomly generated (?) dungeon crawler, where you have to activate five altars and then escape through a portal. Pretty easy, if it wasn't for how unforgiving is the game, enemies that don't give you any chance if you don't kite or cheese. I wanted to like this game so I gave it a chance, but all the very well modelled genitals and the overall pleasant graphic couldn't keep me playing more than 20 minutes, and that's including looking through the (limited) options, tutorials and exploring the menu. There is a multiplayer mode, but as far as I can tell is dead and not even working: I tried to create a game but it wouldn't start, perhaps you have to wait that other people join your lobby before actually starting the game, perhaps is bugged, either way it was a disappointment. I've to give this game credit for two things, though; one is that the graphic is somewhat redeeming (although that alone can't justify the purchase). The other one is truly remarkable and is the simplicity of the tutorial, which explains how the game works through a short series of images and animations: minimal and sometimes cute in the way things are drawn, it should stand as an example about how long and complex a tutorial should be, as well as what role it should play in a game. 4/10", "appid": "726360", "steamid": "profiles/76561197989240599", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "24", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1594209600.0}
