{"text": "The spells are over-designed and ask for a level of precision that the player not only can't but shouldn't apply. You don't want your attention split between aiming spells and defending yourself, as a lot of accidental trading will occur. Trading is a big no-no in roguelikes because you don't always have control over when you can recover health. Health is your momentum, and to lose it is to lose momentum. Therefore, the best way to play this game is to focus on dodging mechanics and not worry about spells missing their targets. It defeats the purpose, and I'm left struggling to find spells that are practical and don't force me out of position. The spell design increases the difficulty artificially. Players like tools that support their good instincts. But the tools you've provided are asking me to ignore my instincts and adapt to something I know is wrong. It doesn't feel good to play as a result. Hostage situations are also a little over-designed. Sometimes, you'll take more damage trying to save them than if you didn't bother. Usually you'll break even in health. But if you're going to ask players to do extra work, you have to reward them extra too. A lot of the mechanics that try to force you to be more careful can be easily worked around or ignored entirely. They don't actually do very much for the game. To its credit, it's pretty fair. Nothing made me angry, and I'm notoriously critical of enemy and level design in games. But it boils down to the various mechanics working against one another, and the game tripping over its own feet. I don't even feel like I was a part of said tripping, but instead I was an onlooker scratching my head because I felt so out of control of what I was doing and what was happening to me.", "appid": "960690", "steamid": "profiles/76561198047561118", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1598184000.0}
